{"title_page": "1917 Great Ankara Fire", "text_new": "{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:1917-Bentderesi-Ankara.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Ulus, Ankara|Bentderesi, Ulus]] (1917)]]\nThe '''1917 Great Ankara Fire''' caused extensive damage to the Turkish city of [[Ankara]] on September 15, 1917.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ba\u011flum |first=Kemal |date=1992 |title=Be\u015fbin Y\u0131lda Nereden Nereye Ankara |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Be%C5%9Fbin_y%C4%B1lda_nereden_nereye_Ankara.html?id=VLm5AQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y |location=Ankara |publisher= |page=194 |isbn=9789759533601 |author-link= }}</ref> Areas affected included the [[Ankara Castle|Hisar\u00f6n\u00fc]], ''\u00c7\u0131kr\u0131k\u00e7\u0131lar Yoku\u015fu'', ''Bedesten'', [[Alt\u0131nda\u011f, Ankara|Sara\u00e7lar Bazaar]] and  ''Atpazar\u0131''. It is estimated that up to 1,900 daggers<ref>{{cite book|url=|title=Anadolu Emraz-\u0131 Sariye Mesaisi|publisher=Ceride-i T\u0131bbiye-i Askeriye|date=September 1917|page=161}}</ref> Laboratuvar\u0131 burned in the city.\n\n==Background==\nAccording to the 1914 census, 69,066 [[Muslims]] and 14,500 [[Christians]] lived in the center of Ankara. Before and after the 1917 fire, successive fires occurred in 20 provinces of Turkey within the space of three years. In these regions, people of various nationalities, mostly Greeks, Jews, and Armenians. They lived in Christian and Jewish communities.<ref>{{web cite|url=http://www.hafizakaydi.org/fotoraflar/|title=1916 Ankara Yang\u0131n\u0131|date=2015|publisher=hafizakaydi.com|language=Turkish}}</ref>  After the fire, two [[mosque]]s and seven [[Church (building)|church]]es remained.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ankara}}\n\n[[Category:History of Ankara]]\n[[Category:1917 fires]]\n[[Category:Fires in Turkey]]\n[[Category:20th century in Ankara]]\n[[Category:Urban fires]]\n", "text_old": "{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:1917-Bentderesi-Ankara.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Ulus, Ankara|Bentderesi, Ulus]] (1917)]]\nThe '''1917 Great Ankara Fire''' caused extensive damage to the the Turkish city of [[Ankara]] on September 15, 1917.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ba\u011flum |first=Kemal |date=1992 |title=Be\u015fbin Y\u0131lda Nereden Nereye Ankara |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Be%C5%9Fbin_y%C4%B1lda_nereden_nereye_Ankara.html?id=VLm5AQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y |location=Ankara |publisher= |page=194 |isbn=9789759533601 |author-link= }}</ref> Areas affected included the [[Ankara Castle|Hisar\u00f6n\u00fc]], ''\u00c7\u0131kr\u0131k\u00e7\u0131lar Yoku\u015fu'', ''Bedesten'', [[Alt\u0131nda\u011f, Ankara|Sara\u00e7lar Bazaar]] and  ''Atpazar\u0131''. It is estimated that up to 1,900 daggers<ref>{{cite book|url=|title=Anadolu Emraz-\u0131 Sariye Mesaisi|publisher=Ceride-i T\u0131bbiye-i Askeriye|date=September 1917|page=161}}</ref> Laboratuvar\u0131 burned in the city.\n\n==Background==\nAccording to the 1914 census, 69,066 [[Muslims]] and 14,500 [[Christians]] lived in the center of Ankara. Before and after the 1917 fire, successive fires occurred in 20 provinces of Turkey within the space of three years. In these regions, people of various nationalities, mostly Greeks, Jews, and Armenians. They lived in Christian and Jewish communities.<ref>{{web cite|url=http://www.hafizakaydi.org/fotoraflar/|title=1916 Ankara Yang\u0131n\u0131|date=2015|publisher=hafizakaydi.com|language=Turkish}}</ref>  After the fire, two [[mosque]]s and seven [[Church (building)|church]]es remained.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ankara}}\n\n[[Category:History of Ankara]]\n[[Category:1917 fires]]\n[[Category:Fires in Turkey]]\n[[Category:20th century in Ankara]]\n[[Category:Urban fires]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1917_Great_Ankara_Fire"}
{"title_page": "Transfer molding", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=November 2016}}\n\n'''Transfer molding'''                                          ('''BrE moulding''') is a manufacturing process where casting material is forced into a mold. Transfer molding is different from [[compression molding]] in that the mold is enclosed [Hayward] rather than open to the fill plunger resulting in higher dimensional tolerances and less environmental impact.<ref name = \"Ornaghi\">{{Cite journal|last1=Ornaghi|first1=Heitor Luiz|last2=Bolner|first2=Alexandre Sonaglio|last3=Fiorio|first3=Rudinei|last4=Zattera|first4=Ademir Jose|last5=Amico|first5=Sandro Campos|date=2010-10-15|title=Mechanical and dynamic mechanical analysis of hybrid composites molded by resin transfer molding|journal=Journal of Applied Polymer Science|language=en|volume=118|issue=2|pages=887\u2013896|doi=10.1002/app.32388|issn=1097-4628}}</ref> Compared to [[Injection moulding|injection molding]], transfer molding uses higher pressures to uniformly fill the mold cavity. This allows thicker reinforcing fiber matrices to be more completely saturated by resin.<ref name=\"Ornaghi\" /> Furthermore, unlike injection molding the transfer mold casting material may start the process as a solid. This can reduce equipment costs and time dependency. The transfer process may have a slower fill rate than an equivalent injection molding processes.<ref name=\"Ornaghi\" />\n\n== Process ==\n[[File:Transfer molding.svg|thumb|Figure 1: Transfer Molding basic process]]\nThe mold interior surfaces may be gel-coated. If desired the mold is first pre-loaded with a reinforcing fiber matrix or preform.<ref name=\"Ornaghi\" /> Fiber content of a transfer molded composite can be as high as 60% by volume. The fill material may be a preheated solid or a liquid. It is loaded into a chamber known as the pot. A ram or plunger forces material from the pot into the heated mold cavity. If feed-stock is initially solid, the forcing pressure and mold temperature melt it.  Standard mold features such as sprue channels, a flow gate and ejector pins may be used. The heated mold ensures that the flow remains liquid for complete filling. Once filled the mold can be cooled at a controlled rate for optimal thermoset curing.\n\n== Variations ==\nThe industry identifies a variety of processes within the transfer molding category.  There are areas of overlap and the distinctions between each method may not be clearly defined.\n\n=== Resin transfer molding ===\n[[File:RTM process.png|thumb|Figure 2: Resin Transfer Molding 1: Cope 2: Drag 3: Clamp 4: Mixing chamber 5: Fiber preform 6: Heated mold 7: Resin 8: Curative]]\nResin transfer molding (RTM) uses a liquid thermoset resin to saturate a fiber preform placed in a closed mold. The process is versatile and can fabricate products with embedded objects such as foam cores or other components in addition to the fiber preform.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kendall|first=K. N.|last2=Rudd|first2=C. D.|last3=Owen|first3=M. J.|last4=Middleton|first4=V.|date=1992-01-01|title=Characterization of the resin transfer moulding process|journal=Composites Manufacturing|volume=3|issue=4|pages=235\u2013249|doi=10.1016/0956-7143(92)90111-7}}</ref>\n\n=== Vacuum assisted resin transfer molding ===\nVacuum assisted transfer molding (VARTM) uses a partial vacuum on one side of a fiber mat to pull the resin in for complete saturation. VARTM uses lower plunger forces which allows molding to be carried out with cheaper equipment.  The use of a vacuum may allow the resin to adequately flow and or cure without heating.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heider|first=Dirk|last2=Graf|first2=A.|last3=Fink|first3=Bruce K.|last4=Gillespie|first4=Jr., John W.|date=1999-01-01|title=Feedback control of the vacuum-assisted resin transfer molding (VARTM) process|volume=3589|pages=133\u2013141|doi=10.1117/12.339956|series=Process Control and Sensors for Manufacturing II}}</ref> This temperature independence allows thicker fiber preforms and larger product geometries to be economical.  VARTM can produce parts with less porosity than regular transfer molding with a proportional increase in casting strength.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hayward|first=J. S.|last2=Harris|first2=B.|date=1990-09-01|title=The effect of vacuum assistance in resin transfer moulding|journal=Composites Manufacturing|volume=1|issue=3|pages=161\u2013166|doi=10.1016/0956-7143(90)90163-Q}}</ref>\n\n=== Micro transfer molding ===\nAlso called transfer micromolding, this is a process that uses a mold to form then transfer structures as small as 30&nbsp;nm onto thin films and microcircuitry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cavallini|first=Massimiliano|last2=Murgia|first2=Mauro|last3=Biscarini|first3=Fabio|date=2002-01-02|title=Direct patterning of tris-(8-hydroxyquinoline)-aluminum (III) thin film at submicron scale by modified micro-transfer molding|journal=Materials Science and Engineering: C|series=Current Trends in Nanotechnologies: From Materials to Systems, Proceedings of Symposium S, EMRS Spring Meeting 2001, Strasbourg France|volume=19|issue=1\u20132|pages=275\u2013278|doi=10.1016/S0928-4931(01)00398-8}}</ref> Unlike normal scale transfer molding, the micro form can and is used with metals as well as non metals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choi|first=Seong-O|last2=Rajaraman|first2=Swaminathan|last3=Yoon|first3=Yong-Kyu|last4=Wu|first4=Xiaosong|last5=Allen|first5=Mark G.|date=2006|title=3-D patterned microstructures using inclined UV exposure and metal transfer micromolding|url=http://mems.seas.upenn.edu/publications/2006/3-D%20Metal%20Patterned%20Microstructure%20using%20Inclined%20UV%20Exposure%20and%20Metal%20Transfer%20Micromolding%20Technology.pdf|journal=Proc. Solid State Sensors, Actuators and Microsystems Workshop (Hilton Head, SC).|doi=|pmid=|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Defects ==\nLimiting defects is key when commercial producing any sort of material. Transfer molding is no exception. For example, voids in a transfer molded parts significantly reduce strength and modulus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kang|first=Moon Koo|last2=Lee|first2=Woo Il|last3=Hahn|first3=H. Thomas|date=2000-09-01|title=Formation of microvoids during resin-transfer molding process|journal=Composites Science and Technology|volume=60|issue=12\u201313|pages=2427\u20132434|doi=10.1016/S0266-3538(00)00036-1}}</ref> There can also be defects when fibers are used around sharp corners. The resin flow can create resin rich zones on the outside of these corners.<ref name=\"Holmberg\">{{Cite journal|last=Holmberg|first=J. A.|last2=Berglund|first2=L. A.|date=1997-01-01|title=Manufacturing and performance of RTM U-beams|journal=Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing|volume=28|issue=6|pages=513\u2013521|doi=10.1016/S1359-835X(97)00001-8}}</ref>\n\n'''Pressure distribution'''\n\nThere are several contributing factors to voids in the final product of transfer molding. One is a non uniform pressure distribution among the material being pressed into the mold. In this case the material folds in on itself and generates voids. Another is voids in the resin being forced into the mold beforehand. This may be obvious, but it is a main contributor. Things to be done to limit these molds include pressing the resin in at a high pressure, keeping the fiber distribution uniform, and using  a high quality properly degassed base resin.\n\n'''Sharp corners'''\n[[File:Defect picture.png|thumb|352x352px|Figure 3: Sharp corner generates voids in transfer molding]]\n\nSharp corners are the problems with all mold based manufacturing, including casting. Specifically in transfer molding corners can break fibers that have been placed in the mold and can create voids on the inside of corners. This effect is demonstrated in Figure 3 on the right. The limiting factor in these designs is the inner corner radius.<ref name=\"Holmberg\" /> This inner radius limit varies depending on resin and fiber selection, but a rule of thumbs is the radius though be 3 to 5 times the laminate thickness.<ref name=\"Holmberg\" />\n\n== Materials ==\nThe material most commonly used for transfer molding is a thermoset polymer. This type of polymer is easy to mold and manipulate, but upon curing, hardens into a permanent form.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GK_yHHypGwMC|title=Thermosetting Polymers|last=Pascault|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sautereau|first2=Henry|last3=Verdu|first3=Jacques|last4=Williams|first4=Roberto J. J.|date=2002-02-20|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9780824744052|language=en}}</ref> For simple homogeneous transfer molded parts, the part is simply made of this plastic substrate. On the other hand, resin transfer molding allows for a composite material to be made by placing a fiber within the mold and subsequently injecting the thermosetting polymer.<ref>{{Citation|last=III|first=William H. Seemann|title=Plastic transfer molding techniques for the production of fiber reinforced plastic structures|date=Feb 20, 1990|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US4902215|accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\nDefects known as voids and dry resin (in the case of resin transfer molding) are possible in transfer molding and often are exacerbated by high viscosity materials. This is because a high viscosity plastic flowing through a thin mold may miss entire vacated areas, leaving air pockets. When air pockets are left in the presence of fiber, this creates a \u201cdry\u201d area, which prevents load from being transferred through the fibers in the dry area.\n\nMaterials used for the plastic are often polyurethanes or epoxy resins. Both of these are soft and malleable before curing, becoming much harder after setting. Materials used for fibers vary extensively, although common choices are carbon or Kevlar fibers, as well as organic fibers, such as hemp.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rouison|first=David|last2=Sain|first2=Mohini|last3=Couturier|first3=M.|date=2006-06-01|title=Resin transfer molding of hemp fiber composites: optimization of the process and mechanical properties of the materials|journal=Composites Science and Technology|volume=66|issue=7\u20138|pages=895\u2013906|doi=10.1016/j.compscitech.2005.07.040}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Molding processes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Underlinked|date=November 2016}}\n\n'''Transfer molding''' ('''BrE moulding''') is a manufacturing process where casting material is forced into a mold. Transfer molding is different from [[compression molding]] in that the mold is enclosed [Hayward] rather than open to the fill plunger resulting in higher dimensional tolerances and less environmental impact.<ref name = \"Ornaghi\">{{Cite journal|last1=Ornaghi|first1=Heitor Luiz|last2=Bolner|first2=Alexandre Sonaglio|last3=Fiorio|first3=Rudinei|last4=Zattera|first4=Ademir Jose|last5=Amico|first5=Sandro Campos|date=2010-10-15|title=Mechanical and dynamic mechanical analysis of hybrid composites molded by resin transfer molding|journal=Journal of Applied Polymer Science|language=en|volume=118|issue=2|pages=887\u2013896|doi=10.1002/app.32388|issn=1097-4628}}</ref> Compared to [[Injection moulding|injection molding]], transfer molding uses higher pressures to uniformly fill the mold cavity. This allows thicker reinforcing fiber matrices to be more completely saturated by resin.<ref name=\"Ornaghi\" /> Furthermore, unlike injection molding the transfer mold casting material may start the process as a solid. This can reduce equipment costs and time dependency. The transfer process may have a slower fill rate than an equivalent injection molding processes.<ref name=\"Ornaghi\" />\n\n== Process ==\n[[File:Transfer molding.svg|thumb|Figure 1: Transfer Molding basic process]]\nThe mold interior surfaces may be gel-coated. If desired the mold is first pre-loaded with a reinforcing fiber matrix or preform.<ref name=\"Ornaghi\" /> Fiber content of a transfer molded composite can be as high as 60% by volume. The fill material may be a preheated solid or a liquid. It is loaded into a chamber known as the pot. A ram or plunger forces material from the pot into the heated mold cavity. If feed-stock is initially solid, the forcing pressure and mold temperature melt it.  Standard mold features such as sprue channels, a flow gate and ejector pins may be used. The heated mold ensures that the flow remains liquid for complete filling. Once filled the mold can be cooled at a controlled rate for optimal thermoset curing.\n\n== Variations ==\nThe industry identifies a variety of processes within the transfer molding category.  There are areas of overlap and the distinctions between each method may not be clearly defined.\n\n=== Resin transfer molding ===\n[[File:RTM process.png|thumb|Figure 2: Resin Transfer Molding 1: Cope 2: Drag 3: Clamp 4: Mixing chamber 5: Fiber preform 6: Heated mold 7: Resin 8: Curative]]\nResin transfer molding (RTM) uses a liquid thermoset resin to saturate a fiber preform placed in a closed mold. The process is versatile and can fabricate products with embedded objects such as foam cores or other components in addition to the fiber preform.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kendall|first=K. N.|last2=Rudd|first2=C. D.|last3=Owen|first3=M. J.|last4=Middleton|first4=V.|date=1992-01-01|title=Characterization of the resin transfer moulding process|journal=Composites Manufacturing|volume=3|issue=4|pages=235\u2013249|doi=10.1016/0956-7143(92)90111-7}}</ref>\n\n=== Vacuum assisted resin transfer molding ===\nVacuum assisted transfer molding (VARTM) uses a partial vacuum on one side of a fiber mat to pull the resin in for complete saturation. VARTM uses lower plunger forces which allows molding to be carried out with cheaper equipment.  The use of a vacuum may allow the resin to adequately flow and or cure without heating.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Heider|first=Dirk|last2=Graf|first2=A.|last3=Fink|first3=Bruce K.|last4=Gillespie|first4=Jr., John W.|date=1999-01-01|title=Feedback control of the vacuum-assisted resin transfer molding (VARTM) process|volume=3589|pages=133\u2013141|doi=10.1117/12.339956|series=Process Control and Sensors for Manufacturing II}}</ref> This temperature independence allows thicker fiber preforms and larger product geometries to be economical.  VARTM can produce parts with less porosity than regular transfer molding with a proportional increase in casting strength.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hayward|first=J. S.|last2=Harris|first2=B.|date=1990-09-01|title=The effect of vacuum assistance in resin transfer moulding|journal=Composites Manufacturing|volume=1|issue=3|pages=161\u2013166|doi=10.1016/0956-7143(90)90163-Q}}</ref>\n\n=== Micro transfer molding ===\nAlso called transfer micromolding, this is a process that uses a mold to form then transfer structures as small as 30&nbsp;nm onto thin films and microcircuitry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cavallini|first=Massimiliano|last2=Murgia|first2=Mauro|last3=Biscarini|first3=Fabio|date=2002-01-02|title=Direct patterning of tris-(8-hydroxyquinoline)-aluminum (III) thin film at submicron scale by modified micro-transfer molding|journal=Materials Science and Engineering: C|series=Current Trends in Nanotechnologies: From Materials to Systems, Proceedings of Symposium S, EMRS Spring Meeting 2001, Strasbourg France|volume=19|issue=1\u20132|pages=275\u2013278|doi=10.1016/S0928-4931(01)00398-8}}</ref> Unlike normal scale transfer molding, the micro form can and is used with metals as well as non metals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choi|first=Seong-O|last2=Rajaraman|first2=Swaminathan|last3=Yoon|first3=Yong-Kyu|last4=Wu|first4=Xiaosong|last5=Allen|first5=Mark G.|date=2006|title=3-D patterned microstructures using inclined UV exposure and metal transfer micromolding|url=http://mems.seas.upenn.edu/publications/2006/3-D%20Metal%20Patterned%20Microstructure%20using%20Inclined%20UV%20Exposure%20and%20Metal%20Transfer%20Micromolding%20Technology.pdf|journal=Proc. Solid State Sensors, Actuators and Microsystems Workshop (Hilton Head, SC).|doi=|pmid=|access-date=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Defects ==\nLimiting defects is key when commercial producing any sort of material. Transfer molding is no exception. For example, voids in a transfer molded parts significantly reduce strength and modulus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kang|first=Moon Koo|last2=Lee|first2=Woo Il|last3=Hahn|first3=H. Thomas|date=2000-09-01|title=Formation of microvoids during resin-transfer molding process|journal=Composites Science and Technology|volume=60|issue=12\u201313|pages=2427\u20132434|doi=10.1016/S0266-3538(00)00036-1}}</ref> There can also be defects when fibers are used around sharp corners. The resin flow can create resin rich zones on the outside of these corners.<ref name=\"Holmberg\">{{Cite journal|last=Holmberg|first=J. A.|last2=Berglund|first2=L. A.|date=1997-01-01|title=Manufacturing and performance of RTM U-beams|journal=Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing|volume=28|issue=6|pages=513\u2013521|doi=10.1016/S1359-835X(97)00001-8}}</ref>\n\n'''Pressure distribution'''\n\nThere are several contributing factors to voids in the final product of transfer molding. One is a non uniform pressure distribution among the material being pressed into the mold. In this case the material folds in on itself and generates voids. Another is voids in the resin being forced into the mold beforehand. This may be obvious, but it is a main contributor. Things to be done to limit these molds include pressing the resin in at a high pressure, keeping the fiber distribution uniform, and using  a high quality properly degassed base resin.\n\n'''Sharp corners'''\n[[File:Defect picture.png|thumb|352x352px|Figure 3: Sharp corner generates voids in transfer molding]]\n\nSharp corners are the problems with all mold based manufacturing, including casting. Specifically in transfer molding corners can break fibers that have been placed in the mold and can create voids on the inside of corners. This effect is demonstrated in Figure 3 on the right. The limiting factor in these designs is the inner corner radius.<ref name=\"Holmberg\" /> This inner radius limit varies depending on resin and fiber selection, but a rule of thumbs is the radius though be 3 to 5 times the laminate thickness.<ref name=\"Holmberg\" />\n\n== Materials ==\nThe material most commonly used for transfer molding is a thermoset polymer. This type of polymer is easy to mold and manipulate, but upon curing, hardens into a permanent form.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GK_yHHypGwMC|title=Thermosetting Polymers|last=Pascault|first=Jean-Pierre|last2=Sautereau|first2=Henry|last3=Verdu|first3=Jacques|last4=Williams|first4=Roberto J. J.|date=2002-02-20|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9780824744052|language=en}}</ref> For simple homogeneous transfer molded parts, the part is simply made of this plastic substrate. On the other hand, resin transfer molding allows for a composite material to be made by placing a fiber within the mold and subsequently injecting the thermosetting polymer.<ref>{{Citation|last=III|first=William H. Seemann|title=Plastic transfer molding techniques for the production of fiber reinforced plastic structures|date=Feb 20, 1990|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US4902215|accessdate=2016-03-08}}</ref>\n\nDefects known as voids and dry resin (in the case of resin transfer molding) are possible in transfer molding and often are exacerbated by high viscosity materials. This is because a high viscosity plastic flowing through a thin mold may miss entire vacated areas, leaving air pockets. When air pockets are left in the presence of fiber, this creates a \u201cdry\u201d area, which prevents load from being transferred through the fibers in the dry area.\n\nMaterials used for the plastic are often polyurethanes or epoxy resins. Both of these are soft and malleable before curing, becoming much harder after setting. Materials used for fibers vary extensively, although common choices are carbon or Kevlar fibers, as well as organic fibers, such as hemp.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rouison|first=David|last2=Sain|first2=Mohini|last3=Couturier|first3=M.|date=2006-06-01|title=Resin transfer molding of hemp fiber composites: optimization of the process and mechanical properties of the materials|journal=Composites Science and Technology|volume=66|issue=7\u20138|pages=895\u2013906|doi=10.1016/j.compscitech.2005.07.040}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Molding processes]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4070:2486:5f6d::1e5c:a0b1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transfer_molding"}
{"title_page": "Riyad Mahrez", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Riyad Mahrez\n|image          = Alg\u00e9rie - Arm\u00e9nie - 20140531 - Riyad Mahrez.jpg\n|image_size     = 200\n|caption        = Mahrez lining up for [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] in 2014\n|fullname       = Riyad Karim Mahrez<ref name=\"2017 Africa Cup of Nations Squad List - Algeria\">{{cite web\n|title          = 2017 Africa Cup of Nations Squad List \u2013 Algeria | url = http://www.cafonline.com/Portals/0/Total%20AFCON%202016/CAN%20Gabon%20Squad%20lists.pdf | publisher = CAF\n|format         = PDF\n|accessdate     = 10 January 2017}}</ref>\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1991|2|21|df=y}}<ref name=PremProfile/>\n|birth_place    = [[Sarcelles]], France\n|height         = 1.79 m<ref name = \"SW\"/>\n|position       = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n|currentclub    = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|clubnumber     = 26\n|youthyears1    = 2004\u20132009\n|youthclubs1    = AAS Sarcelles\n|years1         = 2009\u20132010\n|clubs1         = [[Quimper Kerfeunteun F.C.|Quimper]]\n|caps1          = 27\n|goals1         = 1\n|years2         = 2010\u20132013\n|clubs2         = [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre II]]\n|caps2          = 60\n|goals2         = 24\n|years3         = 2011\u20132014\n|clubs3         = [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]]\n|caps3          = 60\n|goals3         = 6\n|years4         = 2014\u20132018\n|clubs4         = [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]\n|caps4          = 158\n|goals4         = 42\n|years5         = 2018\u2013\n|clubs5         = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|caps5          = 50\n|goals5         = 14\n|nationalyears1 = 2014\u2013\n|nationalteam1  = [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 56\n|nationalgoals1 = 15\n|club-update    = 18:31, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n|ntupdate       = 23:00, 15 October 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Riyad Karim Mahrez''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 \u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u0645\u062d\u0631\u0632}}; born 21 February 1991) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for {{English football updater|ManchesC}} club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and captains the [[Algeria national football team|Algerian national team]].\n\nMahrez began his career as a youth player for French club AAS Sarcelles. He turned professional in 2009 with [[Quimper Kerfeunteun F.C.|Quimper]], where he played for only one season before moving to [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]], spending a total of three years with them, initially playing for their reserve team and then becoming a first-team regular. In January 2014, Mahrez signed for English side [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], helping them win the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] and promotion to the Premier League at the end of his first season. In the 2015\u201316 season he was the [[Algerian Footballer of the Year]], the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]], and was a member of the Premier League [[PFA Team of the Year]] as he helped Leicester City win the [[2015\u201316 Premier League|Premier League]]. He signed for Manchester City in 2018, winning the Premier League, [[FA Cup]] and [[EFL Cup]] in his first season.\n\nBorn in France, Mahrez made his international debut for [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] in 2014 and represented them at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] and at the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]], [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|2017]] and [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|2019]] [[Africa Cup of Nations]], winning the African Cup of Nations in 2019. In 2016 he was named [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]]'s [[African Footballer of the Year]].\n\n==Early life==\nMahrez was born in [[Sarcelles]], France, to an Algerian father and a mother of Algerian and Moroccan descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djazairess.com/fr/letemps/140838|title=Riyad Mahrez : \"On a une \u00e9quipe capable de faire de belles choses\"|date=10 January 2015|accessdate=6 March 2016|language=French|publisher=DjaZairess}}</ref> His father Ahmed was from [[Beni Snous]], [[Tlemcen District]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lebuteur.com/article/detail?id=33412|title=Mahrez honor\u00e9 \u00e0 Tlemcen|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=28 January 2016|language=French|publisher=El Heddaf}}</ref> Growing up, Mahrez would regularly spend his holidays in Algeria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lebuteur.com/article/detail?id=4572&titre=comment-la-faf-a-chipe-mahrez-au-maroc|title=Comment la FAF a chip\u00e9 Mahrez au Maroc|date=9 May 2014|accessdate=10 June 2014|language=French|publisher=Le Buteur}}</ref><ref name=doyle>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/sep/12/leicester-city-riyad-mahrez-father-dream-algeria-world-cup|title=Leicester City's Riyad Mahrez is fast fulfilling his late father's dreams|date=12 September 2015|accessdate=14 September 2015|author=Paul Doyle|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> His childhood friends included fellow footballers such as [[Wissam Ben Yedder]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ben Yedder's unquestionable self-belief driving him to reach new heights|url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/about-uefa/news/newsid=2518566.html|accessdate=23 November 2017|publisher=UEFA|date=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nMahrez's father had played football in Algeria.<ref name=doyle/> When Mahrez was fifteen, his father died of a heart attack. He reflected that \"I don't know if I started to be more serious but after the death of my dad things started to go for me. Maybe in my head, I wanted it more\".<ref name=doyle/>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nAlthough often overlooked by teams due to his slender build, Mahrez developed ball skills that brought him attention.<ref name=doyle/>\n\nHe joined AAS Sarcelles in 2004.<ref name = \"journey\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35688719|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester forward's journey to top of Premier League|date=10 March 2016|accessdate=10 March 2016|author=Steve Crossman|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Mahrez joined [[Championnat de France amateur|CFA]] side [[Quimper Kerfeunteun F.C.|Quimper]] from AAS Sarcelles, making 22 appearances and scoring 2 goals in his first season with the club.<ref name=\"Quimper\">{{cite web|url=http://stat2foot.com/qrclubs/quimper0910.htm |language=French |title=QUIMPER 17e CFA Groupe D |publisher=Stat2foot.com |accessdate=11 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111075652/http://stat2foot.com/qrclubs/quimper0910.htm |archivedate=11 January 2014 }}</ref> While playing for Quimper he lived with [[Mathias Pogba]].<ref name = \"journey\"/>\n\nHe joined [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]] in 2010, turning down offers from leading French teams [[Paris Saint-Germain]] and [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] to join them, being enticed by their youth system.<ref name=doyle/> He initially played for their reserve team, Le Havre II, before going on to play 60 times and score 6 goals for the first team in the French [[Ligue 2]] from 2011 until leaving in January 2014.<ref name = \"SW\"/><ref>{{LFP|id=mahrez-riyad|name=Riyad Mahrez}}</ref> He criticised Ligue 2 for what he saw as a reliance on defence and teams aiming for a goalless draw in every match.<ref name=doyle/>\n\n===Leicester City===\n[[File:Riyad Mahrez.jpg|thumb|right|Mahrez playing for Leicester in 2014]]\n[[File:Mahrez free kick 1 (16476351346).jpg|thumb|303px|Mahrez taking a free kick away to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in February 2015.]]\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\nWhile Mahrez was playing for Le Havre, English [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]'s scout [[Steve Walsh (scout)|Steve Walsh]] was monitoring teammate [[Ryan Mendes]], but was instead impressed by Mahrez.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City star Riyad Mahrez not target of original scouting mission says head of recruitment|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Riyad-target-scouting-mission/story-28029571-detail/story.html|accessdate=26 April 2016|work=Leicester Mercury|date=22 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129020313/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Riyad-target-scouting-mission/story-28029571-detail/story.html|archivedate=29 November 2015}}</ref> Mahrez had never heard of Leicester, whom he initially presumed to be a rugby club.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brewin|first1=Joe|title=Riyad Mahrez: The street-schooled dreamer whose ambition knew no limits|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/riyad-mahrez-street-schooled-dreamer-whose-ambition-knew-no-limits|accessdate=1 September 2016|work=FourFourTwo|date=25 April 2016}}</ref> On 11 January 2014, he signed a three-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/news/article/110114-riyad-mahrez-signs-for-leicester-city-1287938.aspx|title=Riyad Mahrez Signs For Leicester City|date=11 January 2014|accessdate=11 January 2014|publisher=Leicester City F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25639726|title=Transfer window: Riyad Mahrez joins Leicester from Le Havre|date=11 January 2014|accessdate=13 January 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His friends and family were initially sceptical of a move to English football due to its physical nature, believing that his style of play would be more suited to Spain.<ref name=doyle/>\n\nMahrez made his debut on 25 January 2014, coming on in the 79th minute as a substitute replacing fellow winger [[Lloyd Dyer]], in the 2\u20130 win against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25789370|title=Leicester 2&nbsp;\u2013 0 Middlesbrough|date=25 January 2014|accessdate=25 January 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> After making four substitute appearances for Leicester, including scoring his first goal for the club, an 82nd-minute equaliser against [[Leicester City F.C.\u2013Nottingham Forest F.C. rivalry|local rivals]] [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], manager Nigel Pearson announced in February 2014 that he thought Mahrez was ready to start games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26278839|title=Riyad Mahrez: Nigel Pearson says winger ready to start games|date=21 February 2014|accessdate=23 February 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Leicester ended [[2013\u201314 Football League Championship|the season]] as winners of the Championship, returning to the Premier League for the first time in ten years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City promoted to Premier League after 10-year absence|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26906091|accessdate=20 December 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=5 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nMahrez made his Premier League debut on 16 August 2014, and scored his first goal in the division on 4 October 2014 in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref name = \"SB\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-news-Unknown-Riyad-Mahrez-making/story-23059629-detail/story.html|title='Unknown' Riyad Mahrez making impressive strides, says Nigel Pearson|date=8 October 2014|accessdate=16 October 2014|publisher=Leicester Mercury|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020150217/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-news-Unknown-Riyad-Mahrez-making/story-23059629-detail/story.html|archivedate=20 October 2014}}</ref> Mahrez was part of the Leicester team that won seven of its final nine matches of the season to avoid relegation to the Football League. He scored both goals in a 2\u20130 defeat of [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 9 May<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/32561831|title=Leicester 2\u20130 Southampton}}</ref> and ended [[2014\u201315 Leicester City F.C. season|the season]] with four goals and three assists from 30 appearances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.premierleague.com/en-gb/players/playerprofile.html/riyad-mahrez|title=Riyad Mahrez|accessdate=20 December 2015|work=Premier League|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222111631/http://m.premierleague.com/en-gb/players/playerprofile.html/riyad-mahrez|archivedate=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nHe signed a new four-year contract with Leicester in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33789418|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City winger signs new contract|date=5 August 2015|accessdate=6 August 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 8 August 2015, Mahrez scored two goals in the season opener against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in a 4\u20132 home win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/08/08/england/premier-league/leicester-city-fc/sunderland-association-football-club/2043050/|title=Leicester City 4\u20132 Sunderland|date=8 August 2015|accessdate=10 August 2015|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> He was later described as the club's \"match winner\" by captain [[Wes Morgan]], following \"superb form\" which saw him score four goals in the first three games of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/t-rely-Mahrez-time-ndash-Wes/story-27760222-detail/story.html|title=We can't rely on Riyad Mahrez all the time, says Wes Morgan|date=9 September 2015|accessdate=9 September 2015|publisher=Leicester Mercury|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911235806/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/t-rely-Mahrez-time-ndash-Wes/story-27760222-detail/story.html|archivedate=11 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter scoring four goals in the opening four games of the 2015\u201316 season, Mahrez was nominated for the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34216391|title=Andre Ayew & Manuel Pellegrini win Premier League awards|date=11 September 2015|accessdate=13 September 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> By 3 November 2015, he had scored seven goals in 10 Premier League games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34709767|title=Riyad Mahrez wary of Leicester City's rising expectations|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 5 December, Mahrez scored a hat-trick as Leicester defeated [[Swansea City F.C.|Swansea City]] 3\u20130 to go top of the Premier League, putting him on ten league goals for the season and making him the first Algerian to score a [[List of Premier League hat-tricks|Premier League hat-trick]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pritchard|first1=Dafydd|title=Swansea 0\u20133 Leicester|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34951743|accessdate=20 December 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=5 December 2015}}</ref> Mahrez and his midfield partners [[Marc Albrighton]], [[N'Golo Kant\u00e9]] and [[Danny Drinkwater]] received plaudits for their part in Leicester's early season run of form,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Laurence|first1=Martin|title=Why Riyad Mahrez, and not Jamie Vardy, has been the player of the season so far|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/who-scored-blog/2015/dec/08/riyad-mahrez-jamie-vardy-player-season-premier-league|accessdate=17 January 2016|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2015}}</ref> and manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] described Mahrez and forward [[Jamie Vardy]] as \"priceless\" ahead of the January transfer window.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jamie Vardy and Riyad Mahrez priceless \u2013 Claudio Ranieri|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35098801|accessdate=17 January 2016|website=BBC Sport|date=15 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 Mahrez's transfer value was said to have risen from \u00a34.5 million to \u00a330.1 million, ranking him among the top 50 most valuable players in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title = Leicester City winger Riyad Mahrez ranked in top 50 most valuable players in Europe at nearly \u00a330m|url = http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-winger-Riyad-Mahrez-ranked-50/story-28475654-detail/story.html|publisher = Leicester Mercury|date = 6 January 2016|accessdate = 7 February 2016}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Leicester City: Why we are all rooting for the Foxes|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35480812|publisher = BBC Sport|date = 3 February 2016|accessdate = 7 February 2016}}</ref> In the same year, Mahrez's popularity in his homeland led Leicester to have over almost three times as many [[Facebook]] fans in Algeria than in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|title=African players in the Premier League|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35844104|accessdate=18 March 2016|website=BBC Sport|date=18 March 2016}}</ref> The barbershop in Sarcelles that he frequented from his childhood became a destination for fans from as far as Belgium, desiring the same haircut.<ref name=\"journey\"/>\n\nMahrez was one of four Leicester players named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] in April 2016,<ref name = \"PFATeam\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36106596|title=PFA awards: Leicester and Spurs dominate Premier League team|date=21 April 2016|accessdate=21 April 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and later that month he won the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] award.<ref name = \"PFAPlayer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36124713|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City forward named PFA Player of the Year|date=25 April 2016|accessdate=25 April 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was the first African to earn the accolade.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bargain of the century Riyad Mahrez first African to win EPL player of the season|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/sport/football/bargain-century-riyad-mahrez-first-african-win-epl-player-season|accessdate=25 April 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=TVNZ|date=25 April 2016}}</ref> When Leicester finished the season as champions, Mahrez became the first Algerian to win a Premier League medal.<ref name = \"PL\">{{cite news|title=Leicester City: The ridiculous statistics|url=http://www.football365.com/news/leicester-city-the-ridiculous-statistics|accessdate=3 May 2016|publisher=Football 365|date=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\n{{Quote box |width=35% |align=right |quoted=1 |quote=I am fiercely ambitious and feel now is the time to move on to a new experience. I've always enjoyed a good relationship with the chairman and everyone at the club, and I hope I have been able to repay the faith shown to me by my performances and commitment on the pitch during my time here. |salign=right |source=\u2014 Mahrez speaking to ''[[The Guardian]]'' about his desire to leave Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/may/30/riyad-mahrez-leicester-city-transfer-request-time-to-move-on |title=Riyad Mahrez asks to leave Leicester: 'I feel now is the time to move on' |date=30 May 2017 |accessdate=3 June 2017 |newspaper=theguardian}}</ref>}}\n\nHe signed a new four-year contract with Leicester in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37112706|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City winger signs new four-year deal|date=17 August 2016|accessdate=18 August 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was nominated for the [[2016 Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]] in October 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37748717|title=Ballon d'Or: Jamie Vardy, Riyad Mahrez, Gareth Bale & Sergio Aguero on shortlist|date=24 October 2016|accessdate=29 October 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> finishing seventh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2016/12/12/ballon-dor-2016-ryad-mahrez-7e-95861.php|title=Ballon d'Or 2016 : Ryad Mahrez 7e !|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=12 December 2016|language=French|publisher=dzfoot.com}}</ref> He won the [[BBC African Footballer of the Year]] award in December 2016.<ref name = \"BBCAfrican\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38210161|title=Riyad Mahrez wins BBC African Footballer of the Year 2016 award|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=12 December 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez did not offer a big season especially with the decline in the level of Leicester much, but helped the team's arrival in the [[2016\u201317 UEFA Champions League#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals of the Champions League]] for the first time, scoring four goals and two assists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39275115|title=Leicester reach Champions League quarter-finals and threaten to defy logic again|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=3 June 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 6 May, Mahrez played his 100th Premier League game for Leicester, against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], scoring in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fr.starafrica.com/football/articles/premier-league-36e-j-100e-match-et-6e-de-mahrez/|title=Premier League (36e J) : 100e match et 6e but de Mahrez !|date=8 May 2017|accessdate=3 June 2017|publisher=fr.starafrica.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2017/05/06/angleterre-6e-but-de-mahrez-pour-sa-100e-en-pl-102774.php|title=Angleterre : 6e but de Mahrez pour sa 100e en PL|date=6 May 2017|accessdate=3 June 2017|publisher=dzfoot.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nAt the end of the 2016\u201317 season, Mahrez announced that he wished to leave the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40098443|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester forward releases statement asking to leave the club|date=30 May 2017|accessdate=30 May 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Following the announcement, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] manager [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] stated his interest in signing Mahrez,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40142219|title=Riyad Mahrez: Arsenal boss Arsene Wenger interested in Leicester winger|date=3 June 2017|accessdate=4 June 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and Italian side [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] had a bid for Mahrez rejected in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40679721|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester reject Roma bid for Algeria winger|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=21 July 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In August 2017 he spoke of his \"focus\" despite his uncertain future at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40911451|title=Riyad Mahrez: Algeria winger 'focused' despite uncertain future|date=12 August 2017|accessdate=22 August 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> The [[Algerian Football Federation]] reported on 31 August, the last day of the transfer window, that it had allowed him to leave the national team and travel quickly to Europe in order to complete his transfer to an interested club; this transfer did not materialise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faf.dz/mahrez-autorise-a-aller-officialiser-son-transfert-vers-son-nouveau-club/|title=Mahrez autoris\u00e9 \u00e0 aller officialiser son transfert vers son nouveau club|date=31 August 2017|accessdate=31 August 2017|publisher=Algerian Football Federation|language=French|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831042018/http://www.faf.dz/mahrez-autorise-a-aller-officialiser-son-transfert-vers-son-nouveau-club/|archivedate=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Riyad Mahrez remains at Leicester despite being released from Algeria squad|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41105659|date=1 September 2017|accessdate=6 October 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In January 2018 he again asked for a transfer away from the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42875848|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City winger hands in transfer request as Man City make bid|date=30 January 2018|accessdate=31 January 2018|author=Simon Stone|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> After a move to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] fell through,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42895613|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester will 'help' winger after Man City walk away from potential deal|date=1 February 2018|accessdate=6 February 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez stopped attending training at Leicester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42918406|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester forward misses training for fourth day|date=2 February 2018|accessdate=2 February 2018|author=Simon Stone|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His behaviour was criticised by commentator and former player [[Chris Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42953586|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester midfielder acting like 'big baby' since move fell through \u2013 Chris Sutton|date=6 February 2018|accessdate=6 February 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez was critical about the \"untrue assumptions\" about his absence from the team,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43001730|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester winger criticises 'untrue assumptions' about absence|date=9 February 2018|accessdate=12 February 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and later thanked his teammates for their support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43331305|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester winger says team-mates stood by him|date=8 March 2018|accessdate=9 March 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester City===\n====2018\u201319 season====\nOn 10 July 2018, [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] confirmed the signing of Mahrez on a five-year contract. The transfer fee of \u00a360m made Mahrez the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|most expensive African footballer]], and also Manchester City's most expensive signing and a record transfer fee received by [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=City sign Riyad Mahrez from Leicester|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/first-team/first-team-news/2018/july/man-city-sign-riyad-mahrez-leicester|accessdate=10 July 2018|work=|date=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44709129?ns_mchannel=social&ns_campaign=bbc_sport&ns_source=facebook&ns_linkname=sport |title=Riyad Mahrez: Manchester City sign winger from Leicester for \u00a360m |website=BBC Sport |date=10 July 2018 |accessdate=10 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=City sign Riyad Mahrez from Leicester|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/first-team/first-team-news/2018/july/man-city-sign-riyad-mahrez-leicester|publisher=Manchester City F.C.|date=10 July 2018}}</ref> He stated he wanted to win the Champions League with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44809552|title=Riyad Mahrez: I want to win Champions League with Manchester City|date=12 July 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=16 July 2018}}</ref> He made his debut as a starter on 5 August, as City defeated Chelsea 2\u20130 to win the [[2018 FA Community Shield]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref name=shield>{{cite news |last1=Bevan |first1=Chris |title=Chelsea 0&ndash;2 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44995783 |accessdate=5 August 2018 |website=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2018}}</ref> On 22 September 2018, coming on as a substitute in the 61st minute Mahrez scored a brace for Citizens against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], The first goal was his first with Manchester City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Riyad Mahrez double caps five-star Manchester City\u2019s rout of Cardiff |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/sep/22/cardiff-manchester-city-premier-league-match-report |accessdate=16 November 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=22 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 October 2018, Mahrez scored the only goal for Manchester City in a 1\u20130 away victory against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. He dedicated the goal to [[Vichai Srivaddhanaprabha]], the former owner of his previous club Leicester City, who had recently [[2018 Leicester City F.C. helicopter crash|died in a helicopter crash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46026701|title=Leicester helicopter crash: Riyad Mahrez dedicates Man City goal to Foxes owner|website=BBC Sport|date=29 October 2018|accessdate=6 November 2018}}</ref> On 24 February 2019, Mahrez won his second title with Man City by winning the [[2018\u201319 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], also won the best player of the Carabao Cup although he did not participate in the final.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bhardwaj |first1=Vaishali |title=Man City beat Chelsea to win EFL Cup Final after Wembley penalty shootout |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/chelsea-vs-man-city-efl-cup-final-report-result-wembley-a4075136.html |work=[[Evening Standard]] |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=League Cup: City s'impose aux tirs au but sans Mahrez |url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2019/02/24/league-cup-city-simpose-aux-tirs-au-but-sans-mahrez-145865.php |work=dzfoot.com |accessdate=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of his first season with Manchester City, despite having \"limited playing time\" (including just 14 league starts),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48260081|title=Manchester City: Riyad Mahrez happy at Premier League champions|date=13 May 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez won the Premier League title for the second time, and his first with Manchester City, becoming the second African player to win the title with two different clubs after [[Kolo Tour\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester City win back-to-back Premier League titles after surviving early Brighton scare |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/05/12/brighton-vs-manchester-city-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |accessdate=14 May 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=PL : Mahrez passeur et buteur, Man. City Champion ! |url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2019/05/12/pl-mahrez-passeur-et-buteur-city-champion-151231.php |accessdate=14 May 2019 |publisher=dzfoot.com |date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Mahrez said he would not leave City despite his lack of game time, claiming that he knew his first season would be difficult and he had come to a stable team with good players but he trusted his potential.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mercato : Mahrez, \u00ab Je n'irai nul part ! \u00bb |url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2019/05/14/mahrez-je-nirai-nul-part-151364.php |accessdate=14 May 2019 |publisher=dzfoot.com |date=14 May 2019}}</ref> A week after in the FA Cup final, he achieved his fourth title of the season after beating [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] 6\u20130 becoming the first African player to complete an English domestic [[Treble (association football)|treble]], as he earlier won the [[2018\u201319 EFL Cup]] and the [[2018\u201319 Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester City smash six past Watford in FA Cup final to win historic domestic treble |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/05/18/fa-cup-final-manchester-city-vs-watford-live-score-latest-updates/ |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019\u201320 season====\nIn August 2019 Mahrez missed the [[2019 FA Community Shield]] over concerns about medicine he had been given by the Algerian national team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49230288|title=Riyad Mahrez: Medicine concern kept Algerian out of Man City team|date=4 August 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> The Algerian FA described it as a \"non-event\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49263769|title=Riyad Mahrez: Concerns over medicine taken by Man City winger a 'non-event', says Algerian FA|date=7 August 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez later started in Manchester City's 5-0 opening day away win against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], being involved in all 5 of his side's goals, providing two assists for hat-trick scorer [[Raheem Sterling]] and winning a penalty for [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]] to eventually score after a retake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49215984|title=West Ham 0-5 Manchester City|date=10 August 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Riyad Mahrez - 2014 World Cup.jpg|thumbnail|right|Mahrez playing for [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].]]\n\nIn November 2013, French-born Mahrez expressed his desire to represent [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/news-14868-verts-riyad-mahrez-je-sais-que-je-peux-jouer-en-en.php |title=Riyad Mahrez \"Je sais que je peux jouer en EN\" |trans-title=Riyad Mahrez \"I know that I can play in the national team\" |language=French |date=11 November 2013 |accessdate=11 January 2014 |publisher=DZFoot |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112090928/http://www.dzfoot.com/news-14868-verts-riyad-mahrez-je-sais-que-je-peux-jouer-en-en.php |archivedate=12 January 2014 }}</ref> He was called up to the provisional Algeria squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27374742|title=World Cup 2014: Nabil Bentaleb in Algeria's 30-man squad|date=12 May 2014|accessdate=12 May 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 31 May 2014, Mahrez made his international debut for the ''Desert Foxes'' as a starter in a pre-World Cup friendly match against [[Armenia national football team|Armenia]], and he was subsequently called up to the full squad for the tournament on 2 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/news/article/020614-world-cup-beckons-for-mahrez-1592375.aspx|title=World Cup Beckons For Mahrez|date=2 June 2014|accessdate=2 June 2014|publisher=Leicester City F.C.}}</ref> The Algerian media were critical of his inclusion and alleged that he had paid manager [[Vahid Halilhod\u017ei\u0107]] for a place in the squad.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tironi|first1=Hrvoje|title=People accused Mahrez of giving me money to go to the World Cup! \u2013 Halilhodzic|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2565/exclusive/2016/02/13/20291192/people-accused-mahrez-of-giving-me-money-to-go-to-the-world|accessdate=4 May 2016|publisher=Goal.com|date=13 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=msn>{{cite news|last1=Ouali|first1=Amer|title=Leicester City and Riyad Mahrez gaining fans in Algeria|url=http://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/premier-league/leicester-city-and-riyad-mahrez-gaining-fans-in-algeria/ar-BBq9qOz|accessdate=4 May 2016|agency=AFP|publisher=MSN|date=29 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603102929/http://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/premier-league/leicester-city-and-riyad-mahrez-gaining-fans-in-algeria/ar-BBq9qOz|archivedate=3 June 2016}}</ref> Mahrez played in the opening group game against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], then was dropped for the remainder of the tournament, in which Algeria reached the last 16.<ref name=msn/>\n\nOn 15 October 2014, Mahrez scored his first international goal, as well as setting up [[Islam Slimani]] in Algeria's 3\u20130, [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|Africa Cup of Nations]] qualifier against [[Malawi national football team|Malawi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/news/article/151014-mahrez-stars-in-algeria-win-2017946.aspx|title=Mahrez Stars In Algeria Win|date=15 October 2014|accessdate=16 October 2014|publisher=Leicester City F.C.}}</ref> In December 2014 he was announced as a member of Algeria's squad for the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|final tournament in Equatorial Guinea]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30477709|title=Nations Cup 2015: Newcastle's Mehdi Abeid in Algeria squad|date=15 December 2014|accessdate=18 December 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> his first meeting was against [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] where he participated in the 60 minutes before the change in the second throw against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] substitute in the last 20 minutes where the Algerian team were defeated by a single goal in their last game in the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations Group C|group stage]] against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] led Mahrez the national team to the quarter-finals, scoring the first goal of a match ending 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Ian|title=Senegal 0\u20132 Algeria|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/30891881|accessdate=20 December 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2015}}</ref> then against [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] gave assists for [[El Arabi Hillel Soudani]] were not enough to exclude from the quarter-finals 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Ian|title=Ivory Coast 3\u20131 Algeria|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/30971819|accessdate=1 February 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=16 January 2017}}</ref> then in the second Round of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CAF Second Round|2018 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Tanzania national football team|Tanzania]] helped Mahrez in the team qualified for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 CAF Third Round|group stage]] where he scored a goal and assists for [[Carl Medjani]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Ian|title=Algeria 7\u20130 Tanzania|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2015/11/17/algerie-tanzanie-live-tweet-77327.php|accessdate=17 November 2015|publisher=DZfoot|date=16 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nMahrez was named in coach [[Georges Leekens]]' Algeria squad for the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Gabon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sofiane Feghouli left out of Algeria's final Africa Cup of Nations squad|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38479829|accessdate=15 January 2017|website=BBC Sport|date=31 December 2016}}</ref> In their opening game, he scored both goals in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Algeria 2 2 Zimbabwe|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38545952|accessdate=15 January 2017|website=BBC Sport|date=15 January 2017}}</ref> and was awarded Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CAF_Online/status/820694598624362496|title=R. Mahrez has been selected as the Total Man of the Match! Well done!|via=Twitter|publisher=CAF|date=15 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, with Algeria's chances of reaching the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] already ended, Mahrez and his (at the time) Leicester teammate [[Islam Slimani]] were dropped from the national team, with coach [[Lucas Alcaraz]] selecting several new players.<ref>{{cite news|title=Algeria look to the future as Mahrez and Slimani are left out of World Cup qualifier|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41455809|accessdate=6 October 2017|website=BBC Sport|date=1 October 2017}}</ref> On 18 November 2018, in the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualifier]] Mahrez scored a brace in a 4\u20131 away victory against [[Togo national football team|Togo]], his first goal with the national team since [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] to lead Algeria to qualify for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Afcon 2019: Mahrez brace helps Algeria qualify for Nations Cup|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46255664|accessdate=18 November 2018|website=BBC Sport|date=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, he was named to Algeria's 23-man squad for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48464422|title=Africa Cup of Nations: Algeria announces 23-man squad|date=30 May 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> By the decision of coach [[Djamel Belmadi]], Mahrez was chosen to be captain of Algeria at the Africa Cup of Nations.<ref>{{cite news|title=EN : le brassard de capitaine sera pour Riyad Mahrez ! |url=https://lagazettedufennec.com/equipe-nationale/selection-a/brassard-de-capitaine-sera-riyad-mahrez/ |accessdate=8 July 2019|publisher=lagazettedufennec.com |date=11 June 2019}}</ref> Mahrez scored a 90+5 minute goal in a 2\u20131 win against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in the semi-finals of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jul/14/algeria-nigeria-match-report|title=Riyad Mahrez strike sinks Nigeria and puts Algeria in Afcon final|website=The Guardian|date=14 July 2019}}</ref> Later on, Algeria managed to win the tournament which was their first since 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/49048899|title=Algeria celebrate second Afcon title after beating Senegal|website=BBC Sport|date=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nA left-footed player, Mahrez usually plays as a right winger, a position which allows him to cut inside and shoot on goal with his stronger foot, or make [[Cross (football)|deliveries]] into the penalty area; however, he is a versatile player, who is capable of playing anywhere across the front line, both in the centre, or on either flank. A quick, creative, and technically gifted player, his main traits are his trickery, balance, turn of pace, flair, and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] skills. Although he is capable of scoring goals, he is also an excellent [[Assist (association football)|assist]] provider, courtesy of his ability to create chances for his tammates. Despite his ability, however, his record from the [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] spot has been inconsistent.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Premier-League/22-03-2016/premier-mahrez-re-leicester-chi-talento-cresciuto-col-calcio-strada-1401130093840.shtml |title=Premier, Mahrez re di Leicester: chi \u00e8 il talento cresciuto col calcio di strada? |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |last1=Boldrini |first1=Stefano |date=23 March 2016 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultimouomo.com/febbre-da-calciomercato-vol-1/ |title=Febbre da Calciomercato vol. 1 |publisher=www.ultimouomo.com |language=Italian |last1=Lisanti |first1=Francesco |date=16 July 2016 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2699952-barcelona-transfer-news-latest-rumours-on-riyad-mahrez-and-jordi-alba |title=Barcelona Transfer News: Latest Rumours on Riyad Mahrez and Jordi Alba |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Jones |first1=Matt |date=25 March 2017 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/analysis-mahrez-and-zahas-divergent-paths/1vegffv6b9lnn1g9fkkfbfr5z1 |title=Analysis: Mahrez and Zaha\u2019s divergent paths |publisher=Goal.com |last1=O'Conners |first1=James |date=23 January 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/club/manchester-city/382/blog/post/3684666/riyad-mahrez-fits-pep-guardiolas-template-while-adding-something-new-to-city |title=Riyad Mahrez fits Pep Guardiola's template while adding something new to City |publisher=ESPN FC |last1=Cox |first1=Michael |date=30 October 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2019/04/22/7-best-right-wingers-in-world-football/ |title=7 Best Right Wingers in World Football |publisher=www.hitc.com |last1=Potts Harmer |first1=Alfie |date=22 April 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/10/08/penalty-taking-woes-riyad-mahrezs-conversion-rate-compares-others/ |title=Penalty taking woes: How Riyad Mahrez's conversion rate compares to others in the Premier League |work=The Telegraph |last1=Field |first1=Pippa |date=5 October 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-penalty-mahrez-liverpool-15253082 |title=The Man City players with the best penalty records revealed after Riyad Mahrez miss vs Liverpool |work=The Manchester Evening News |last1=Brennan |first1=Stuart |date=8 October 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2777465-leicester-city-reportedly-value-riyad-mahrez-at-75m-amid-man-city-rumours |title=Leicester City Reportedly Value Riyad Mahrez at \u00a375M Amid Man City Rumours |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Jones |first1=Matt |date=23 May 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref> During his time at Manchester City under manager Pep Guardiola, Mahrez was also able to improve his defensive skills and work-rate, as well as his decision\u2013making.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/riyad-mahrez-man-city-pep-guardiola-changed-winger-tottenham-hotspur |title=How Pep Guardiola has transformed Riyad Mahrez from \u00a360m substitute into the kind of winger he demands |publisher=FourFourTwo |last1=Wilkes |first1=Paul |date=16 August 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/mahrez-man-city-tactics-guardiola-17149849 |title=Man City star Riyad Mahrez pinpoints two parts of his game he has had to improve |work=The Manchester Evening News |last1=Brennan |first1=Stuart |date=25 October 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/mahrez-lifts-lid-on-his-initial-struggle-to-adapt-to/1tcofom30uusa1cd1wftpoglpl |title=Mahrez lifts lid on his initial struggle to adapt to Guardiola\u2019s demands at Manchester City |publisher=Goal.com |last1=Adewoye |first1=Gbenga |date=29 October 2019 |accessdate=5 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMahrez married his English girlfriend Rita Johal in 2015.<ref name=doyle/><ref>{{cite web|title=Mais qui est Rita, la tr\u00e8s jolie femme de Mahrez ?|url=http://www.sports.fr/football/angleterre/articles/rita-la-tres-jolie-femme-de-riyad-mahrez-1505289/|website=Sports.fr|accessdate=6 June 2016|language=French|date=30 April 2016}}</ref> Their daughter was born later that year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Percy|first1=John|title='Flying' Riyad Mahrez coming to terms with dramatic ascent and comparisons with Lionel Messi|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leicester-city/12048440/Flying-Riyad-Mahrez-coming-to-terms-with-dramatic-ascent-and-comparisons-with-Lionel-Messi.html|accessdate=27 April 2016|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 December 2015}}</ref> In June 2019 the couple, who by that time had two daughters, were ordered to pay a former nanny her unpaid wages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-48770058|title=Riyad Mahrez ordered to compensate nanny|date=26 June 2019|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nMahrez is a practising Muslim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/thriving-premier-league-shining-example-6842237|title=Thriving Premier League a shining example of multiculturalism in week of Paris terrorist attack|date=16 November 2015|accessdate=28 April 2016|author=Dave Kidd|publisher=Daily Mirror}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Duch\u00e2teau|first1=Romain|title=Riyad Mahrez, l'enfant ch\u00e9ri de Sarcelles|url=http://www.sofoot.com/riyad-mahrez-l-enfant-cheri-de-sarcelles-207264.html|accessdate=13 May 2016|publisher=SoFoot|date=29 August 2015|language=French}}</ref> In June 2017, he made the [[Umrah]] pilgrimage to [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0631\u064a\u0627\u0636 \u0645\u062d\u0631\u0632 \u064a\u0624\u062f\u064a \u0645\u0646\u0627\u0633\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0645\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0643\u0631\u0645\u0629|url=https://arabic.cnn.com/sport/2017/06/12/mahrez-omrah-mecca-algeria|accessdate=13 June 2017|publisher=CNN|date=12 June 2017|language=Arabic}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 8 March 2020}}<ref name = \"Quimper\"/><ref name = \"SW\">{{soccerway|riyad-mahrez/156662|accessdate=13 May 2019}}</ref><ref name = \"SB\">{{soccerbase|74357|accessdate=27 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.riyad.mahrez.97374.fr.html| title = Riyad Mahrez | accessdate = 20 September 2016 | p